You cannot use the output of a Snowflake stored procedure directly. If you want to get its return output, you need to run another query. This is true whether it&#39;s running from the web UI or through a driver or connector:

    call sp_poc();
    
    select * from table(result_scan(last_query_id()));

If you don&#39;t want to depend on the `last_query_id()` function, you can capture the query ID in the JDBC call. You can refer to the `getQueryId()` method of the Snowflake JDBC driver here:

https://docs.snowflake.com/en/user-guide/jdbc-api.html#interface-snowflakecallablestatement

If you capture the query ID that way, you can then get the output results of the SP for up to 24 hours after its completion using:

    select * from table(result_scan(?));

Where the bind variable is the query ID returned from the `getQueryId()` JDBC method.

